Here we will be analyzing the D-linking experiment only, so well create a couple of filtered dataframes. One for the D-linking data:

# Get D-link items
dlink.conditions <- c("ShortBare", "ShortD", "ShortDOf", "LongBare", "LongD", "LongDOf")
df.english.dlink <- df.english %>% filter(condition %in% dlink.conditions)

# Reorder levels
df.english.dlink$condition <- factor(df.english.dlink$condition, levels = c("ShortBare", "ShortD", "ShortDOf", "LongBare", "LongD", "LongDOf"))

# Summary
df.english.dlink %>% group_by(condition) %>% summarize(count=n(), mean=mean(zscore), sd=sd(zscore), se=sd / sqrt(count)) %>% ungroup()

Planned contrasts

Just for fun, here is contrast coding for running a 2x3 as a 1x6 (to remind myself how to do it). It doesnt take into account random effects, so its not actually the best model for the data. There was a significant main effect of short (\(\mu = 0.922\)) vs.long (\(\mu = 0.793\)): sentences with shorter distances between the filler and the gap were more acceptable (\(t[1338] = 3.660, CI = [0.179, 0.594], p = 0\)).

(0.9415383 + 0.9066709 + 0.9170072) / 3 #MeanShort
## [1] 0.9217388
(0.7415659 + 0.7836209 + 0.8533297) / 3 #MeanLong
## [1] 0.7928388
# Define contrasts
contrasts(df.english.dlink$condition) <- cbind(c(1,1,1,-1,-1,-1), # Short     v. Long
                                               c(1,-1,0,1,-1,0),  # Bare      v. D
                                               c(1,0,-1,1,0,-1),  # Bare      v. DOf
                                               c(1,-1,0,-1,1,0),  # Int1
                                               c(1,0,-1,-1,0,1))  # Int2

# Run ANOVA
dlink.out.aov <- aov(zscore ~ condition, data=df.english.dlink)
summary(dlink.out.aov)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
## condition      5    7.2  1.4308   3.433 0.00436 **
## Residuals   1338  557.6  0.4167                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Run contrasts
fit.contrast(dlink.out.aov, "condition", 
        rbind("ME1.ShortVLong"        = c(1,1,1,-1,-1,-1),
              "ME2.BarevD"            = c(1,-1,0,1,-1,0),
              "ME3.BarevDOf"          = c(1,0,-1,1,0,-1),
              "Int1.LengthxD"         = c(1,-1,0,-1,1,0),
              "Int2.LengthxDOf"       = c(1,0,-1,-1,0,1)), 
        df=T, conf.int=0.95, show.all=TRUE)

Mixed-effects model

In order to do a proper 2x3, the data must be recoded, so we do that here.

df.english.dlink <- df.english.dlink %>% 
  mutate(distance=ifelse(
    condition=="ShortBare" | condition == "ShortD" | condition=="ShortDOf", "Short", "Long"), 
    dlink=ifelse(
      condition=="ShortBare" | condition=="LongBare", "Bare", 
      ifelse(condition=="ShortD" | condition=="LongD", "D", "DOf")
      ),
    dlinkBin=ifelse(
      condition=="ShortBare" | condition=="LongBare", "Bare", "DLink"
      )
    )

# Create factors
df.english.dlink$distance    <- factor(df.english.dlink$distance, levels=c("Short", "Long"))
df.english.dlink$dlink       <- factor(df.english.dlink$dlink, levels=c("Bare", "D", "DOf"))
df.english.dlink$dlinkBin    <- factor(df.english.dlink$dlinkBin, levels=c("Bare", "DLink"))

# Summaries
df.english.dlink %>% group_by(distance, dlink) %>% summarize(count=n(), mean=mean(zscore), sd=sd(zscore), se=sd / sqrt(count)) %>% ungroup()

Mixed-effects model

Finally, we fit a linear mixed-effects regression, which finds a main effect of distance between filler and gap (\(t[7.926] = 17.334, p = 0\)).

# Define contrasts
contrasts(df.english.dlink$distance) <- cbind(c(-1, 1))
contrasts(df.english.dlink$dlink)    <- cbind(c(1, -1, 0), c(1, 1, -2))

# Linear mixed-effects

# Note: Can't do by-item intercepts because they're not properly labeled
# Note2: Attempting to include random slopes gives singular fit warning, unclear why

out.lmer <- lmer(zscore ~ distance*dlink + (1 | participant) + (1 | list) + (1 | order), data=df.english.dlink)
summary(out.lmer)
